"1300":"1300","about 1325":"about 1325","1387":"1387","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","1339":"1339","Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Paynel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Payne","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."]}]},{"name":"Baron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, English, Dutch, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and Croatian; Breton (also <b>Le Baron</b>): from Old French <i>barun</i>, <i>baron</i>, Middle English <i>barun</i>, <i>baroun</i>, Middle Dutch <i>baroen</i>, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and dialectal Croatian <i>baron</i> ‘baron’ (i.e. a nobleman ranking below an earl and above a knight), a title of nobility which was in England also awarded to certain freemen of the cities of London and York and of the Cinque Ports. As a surname it is unlikely to be a status name denoting a person of rank. Generally, it referred to service in a baronial household or was acquired as a nickname by a peasant who had ideas above his station or applied to a man showing characteristics of a nobleman. See also 3 and 4 below, compare   Barron   and   Lebaron  .","French: habitational name from (Le) Baron, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lebaron  .","German: status name for a freeman or baron, from <i>barūn</i> ‘imperial or church official’, a loanword in Middle High German from Old French (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Barron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Francisco, Carlos, Miguel, Raul, Pedro, Ruben, Alfredo, Luis.","Scottish: status name from Scots <i>baron</i>, which in the Highlands denoted a small proprietary landholder. In Angus it alluded specifically to a tenant of one of the small baronies attached to the Abbey of Coupar Angus. The surname was taken by Scottish migrants to Ulster. Compare   Baron  .","Scottish: shortened form of <b>McBarron</b>, from Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bharain</b> ‘son of the baron’. See   Baron   and 1 above."]},{"name":"Boron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Krystyna, Edyta, Leszek, Mieczyslaw, Mieczyslawa, Wladyslaw.","Polish (<b>Boroń</b>): from a pet form of the personal names <i>Borzysław</i> or <i>Borzymir</i>, formed with the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic <i>boriti se</i>).","French: habitational name from a place so called in Franche-Comté."]},{"name":"Baro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Manuel, Ana, Angel, Carlos, Cesar, Fernando, Jesus, Jose, Orlando, Ramon, Rosalia.  Italian Guido, Angelo, Carmelo, Federico, Lucio.","Catalan (<b>Baró</b>): status name from <i>baró</i> ‘free man, baron’ (see   Baron   1), or a habitational name from a place so named.","Hungarian (<b>Báró</b>): status name from <i>báró</i> ‘baron’. In the form <b>Baró</b>, it could be from a pet form of the personal names <i>Barabás</i> (see   Barabas  ) or <i>Bertalan</i>."]},{"name":"Barona","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of <b>Barón</b> ‘baron’ (see   Baron  ), applied as a nickname or as an occupational name for a member of the household of a baroness.","Italian: probably from the feminine form of   Barone  . The name is concentrated in Sondrio province (Lombardy)."]},{"name":"Barren","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Baron   or   Barran  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hambye,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hanby near Welton le Marsh, in Lincolnshire, which is named from the Old Norse personal name <i>Hundi</i> + Old Norse <i>býr</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hanby","meanings":["English: variant of   Hamby  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Foulques V Paynel - Baron de Hambye, Seigneur de Bricqueville was born in 1302, in Normandy, France, his father, Guillaume de PAYNEL Baron de Hambye , seigneur de Fumechon, Bréhal et Bricqueville, was 32 and his mother, Marguerite d'AVAUGOUR, was 27. He had at least 6 sons and 2 daughters with Agnes de Chanteloup. He died in 1350, in his hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1302–1350":"1302–1350","1295–1339":"1295–1339","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1300–1372":"1300–1372","1318–1361":"1318–1361","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1335–1400":"1335–1400","–1364":"–1364","–1366":"–1366","–1376":"–1376","–1379":"–1379","–1387":"–1387","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1325":"1325","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1379":"1379","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1300":"1300","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1387":"1387","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","1339":"1339","Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1302–1350":"1302–1350","1295–1339":"1295–1339","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1300–1372":"1300–1372","1318–1361":"1318–1361","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1335–1400":"1335–1400","–1364":"–1364","–1366":"–1366","–1376":"–1376","–1379":"–1379","–1387":"–1387","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1325":"1325","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1379":"1379","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1300":"1300","about 1325":"noin 1325","1387":"1387","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","1339":"1339","Hambye, Manche, Normandy, France":"Hambye, Manche, Normandie, Ranska","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska","France":"Ranska